=89tienne,=20
>> France)
>>
>> *Keywords:* Signed graphs analysis, Graph partitioning, Data=20
>> analysis, Public procurements
>> *
>> **Context:*
>> In many applications, the data to be studied is of relational nature,=20
>> modeled in the form of a network and represented by graphs. This=20
>> representation makes possible the study of interactions between=20
>> people, especially in social sciences. Although network analysis is=20
>> an active branch of data mining and machine learning, a majority of=20
>> works focuses on homogeneous networks de-scribed by a simple graph=20
>> where the nodes correspond to the entities of the network and the=20
>> links (edges or arcs) to their relationships.=C2=A0 However, in many=20
>> applications, contextual infor-mation describing the relationships or=20
>> the entities themselves are available and could be used to study in a=20
>> more efficient way the network.
>> This led notably to the notions of signed graphs and attributed=20
>> graphs. In a signed graph, each edge is labeled with either a=20
>> negative or a positive sign, which allows representing antagonistic=20
>> relationships [1].=C2=A0 In an attributed network, vertices are descri=
bed=20
>> by attributes which allow to take into account their individual=20
>> characteristics, like for instance their genre or age [2].
>> These representations are much richer than a simple graph and permit=20
>> to better model com-plex interaction systems. However, they require=20
>> to adapt existing algorithms or to design new ones for solving=20
>> efficiently all standard network visualization and analysis tasks,=20
>> such as com-munity detection, link prediction or information diffusion=
.
>> This=C2=A0 PhD is part of the French Research project DeCoMaP (Detecti=
ng=20
>> Corruption in Markets for Public Procurement) funded by the ANR=20
>> (French NSF) which aims at retrieving, processing and analyzing open=20
>> data related to French public procurements, in order to design a tool=20
>> able to assess corruption risks between public buyers and suppliers.
>>
>> *Subject:*
>> Designing automatic tools for the assessment of risks of corruption=20
>> in public procurements is a task called red flagging. It is not=20
>> completely new, as some teams have been working on it for a few years=20
>> [1], especially at the European level [2]. However, none of them=20
>> applies to French public procurements, as they do not handle its=20
>> specifics (legal framework, nature and form of the available open=20
>> data). Moreover, existing approaches focus on individual information,=20
>> which characterize buyers and suppliers independently, and ignore=20
>> relational information, which cor-responds to interactions and=20
>> interdependencies between these agents.
>> In the context of the project DoCoMaP, we propose to design a new=20
>> tool tackling these issues and limitations. More specifically, the=20
>> goal of this thesis is to handle a large methodological part of this=20
>> work, by representing the relationships between buyers and suppliers=20
>> (normal con-tractual relationship or corruption) and by=20
>> characterizing these agents through signed and/or attributed graphs.
>> As this type of graphs has been much less explored than simple graphs=20
>> in the literature, the first task of this thesis consists in=20
>> designing methods to extract them from the raw data, and to analyze=20
>> them in the context of our application (corruption detection). In=20
>> particular, it is neces-sary to define a corruption index that could=20
>> be used to enrich the information already available in the graph at=20
>> the level of its links (contracts between a public buyer and a=20
>> supplier) and at the level of its vertices (characteristics of the=20
>> actors).
>> The second task focuses on signed graph partitioning in the framework=20
>> of structural balance [3]. A signed graph is said to be balanced if=20
>> it can be partitioned into two [4] or more [5] mutu-ally hostile=20
>> subgroups, each having internal solidarity (i.e. positive edges are=20
>> inside clusters, and negative ones are between them). Some recent=20
>> works started tackling this problem notably in our team [6], but=20
>> there is still much to do for formalizing the problem and solving it=20
>> efficiently, particularly using deep learning approaches [7]. In=20
>> DeCoMap, signed graph partitioning will aim to bring out groups of=20
>> agents (public buyers and supplier companies) likely to be related in=20
>> fraudulent practices.
>>
